      "type": "action",
      "tool": "bash",
      "code": "{\"command\": \"python -c \\\"\\nimport pypdf\\nwith open(r'C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Downloads\\\\Binary Intent Gateway BIG.pdf', 'rb') as f:\\n    reader = pypdf.PdfReader(f)\\n    print('Pages:', len(reader.pages))\\n    for i in range(min(5, len(reader.pages))):\\n        text = reader.pages[i].extract_text()\\n        if text:\\n            print('--- Page', i+1, '---')\\n            print(text[:3000])\\n\\\" 2>&1\", \"description\": \"Extract text from Binary Intent Gateway PDF\"}",
      "output": "Pages: 3\r\n--- Page 1 ---\r\nSovereign Clinical Governance: Implementing 3NFI via the\r\nBinary Intent Gateway (B.I.G.)\r\nAndrea Kwabena Enning\r\nAndieKobbieTech, United Kingdom\r\nApril 2026\r\nAbstract\r\nThe rapid integration of autonomous agents into clinical workflows presents a critical\r\nchallenge to system integrity. Current agentic architectures; which rely on Large Language\r\nModels (LLMs) to perform both linguistic parsing and executive decision-making; are fun-\r\ndamentally vulnerable to In-Band signalling exploits; such as prompt injection and semantic\r\ndrift. We introduce the Binary Intent Gateway (B.I.G.), a protocol that formalises agen-\r\ntic control via a bifurcated [the structural separation of the cognitive-interpretation and\r\nexecutive-enforcement planes] architecture. By applying the principles of 3rd-Normal-Form\r\nIntent (3NFI)—a framework adapted from relational database normalisation—we reduce\r\nagentic reasoning to a discrete, 5-bit Instruction Set Architecture (ISA). Our implementa-\r\ntion provides a deterministic security manifold for the OpenMRS ecosystem; ensuring that\r\nhigh-stakes clinical actions are transitively bound to authorised infrastructure policies rather\r\nthan non-deterministic reasoning traces.\r\n1 Introduction: The Great Forgetting\r\nFor several decades; the fields of Natural Language Understanding (NLU) and formal verifica-\r\ntion were centred on deterministic intent mapping. As Bengio (2013) observed, language resides\r\non a geometric manifold; and the primary challenge of system design was ensuring that lin-\r\nguistic inputs accurately mapped to executable state transitions. However; the emergence of\r\ntransformer-based architectures led to what we term \"The Great Forgetting\"; a period where\r\nthe industry prioritised linguistic fluidity over structural determinism.\r\nModern LLM agents are engineered to be \"helpful\" at the expense of integrity. As Tziakouris\r\n(2026) observe; prompt injection is the modern equivalent of 1970s audio-frequency exploitation;\r\nbecause instructions and data occupy the same signaling channel. If an agent is permitted\r\nto reason about its own security, it effectively bypasses the control plane. We propose the\r\nB.I.G. Protocol as a necessary restoration of order; a return to the rigorous principles of system\r\nengineering.\r\n2 3NFI: A Framework for Deterministic Intent\r\nTobridgethegapbetweenhumanlanguageandclinicalaction; weinvoketherelationalprinciples\r\nestablished by Codd (1970). We define the Third-Normal-Form of Intent (3NFI) to govern\r\nautonomous agents:\r\n1.1NF (Atomic Resolution):Every conversational input must resolve to a singular,\r\nunique, 5-bit Binary OpCode.\r\n2.2NF (Parameter Decoupling):TheAction(the OpCode) must be independent of the\r\nTarget(the patient record); allowing for granular authorisation policies.\r\n1\r\n--- Page 2 ---\r\n3.3NF (Non-T ransitive Reasoning):The authorisation of an action must not depend on\r\nthe LLM’s reasoning trace; it must depend solely on the cryptographic Policy Manifold.\r\n3 The Bifurcated Architecture\r\nOur architecture employs a bifurcated [the structural separation of the cognitive-interpretation\r\nand executive-enforcement planes] approach to separate the \"Guest\" model from the \"Kernel\"\r\nrouter.\r\n3.1 Worktree B: The Cognitive Parser\r\nWe utilise 1-bit ternary models (e.g., BitNet b1.58 (Wang et al., 2024)) as the semantic NIC.\r\nThis model operates in the untrusted Guest plane; its sole function is to reduce complex clinical\r\nnarratives into the 32-Instruction ISA defined in Table 1.\r\n3.2 Worktree A: The Enforcement Manifold\r\nThe Control Plane is managed by the B.I.G. Gateway, an immutable, Rust-based service. It\r\nvalidates every OpCode against a Weaviate-indexed Policy Manifold. By leveraging Wilson\r\n(2026)’s findings on the \"Geometry of Trust\"; we verify that the intent is geometrically consistent\r\nwith the organisation’s authorised behaviour.\r\nOpCode Mnemonic OpenMRS REST API Mapping\r\n0x00 READ_UNIT GET /ws/rest/v1/patient/{uuid}\r\n0x05 WRITE_OBS POST /ws/rest/v1/obs\r\n0x0A WRITE_ENCOUNTER POST /ws/rest/v1/encounter\r\n0x14 FIN_TRANS POST /ws/rest/v1/billing/transaction\r\n0x1C GOV_DEBUG Intent Ambiguity Fallback\r\nTable 1: Operational mapping of the AK-ISA to OpenMRS.\r\n4 The Sovereign Edge\r\nThe B.I.G. Protocol is designed for operational continuity. Through Zero-Downtime Policy\r\nPropagation (ZDPP); we update our security manifolds in less than 2 milliseconds using gRPC\r\nbinary streams. This eliminates the \"Cold-Start\" vulnerabilities associated with traditional\r\nguardrail deployment; ensuring that critical systems remain protected by current standards\r\nwithout requiring service interruptions.\r\n5 Discussion: The Path to Industrial Autonomy\r\nThe B.I.G. Protocol represents a fundamental shift in the agentic enterprise. While current\r\napproaches seek to align models via linguistic post-processing, we argue for the formalisation of\r\na \"Sovereign Control Plane.\" By treating human intent as a structured, binary-routable packet,\r\nwe restore the deterministic security that has enabled the stability of the global financial and\r\nclinical networks for decades.\r\n2\r\n--- Page 3 ---\r\nReferences\r\nBengio, Y. (2013) ‘Representation Learning: A Review and New Perspectives’,IEEE Transac-\r\ntions on Pattern Analysis and Machine Intelligence.\r\nChakrabarty, A. (2026) ‘Defending 20 Trillion Transactions: How Hyperforce’s Trusted Perime-\r\nter Stops DDoS Attacks’,Salesforce Engineering Journal.\r\nCodd, E. F. (1970) ‘A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks’,Communications\r\nof the ACM, 13(6), pp. 377–387.\r\nEnning, A. K. (2026) ‘The Binary Intent Gateway: A Formal Specification’,AndieKobbieTech\r\nResearch Archives.\r\nTziakouris, G. (2026) ‘Prompt injection is the new SQL injection, and guardrails aren’t enough’,\r\nCisco AI Blog.\r\nWang, H., Ma, S., et al. (2024) ‘The era of 1-bit llms: All large language models are in 1.58\r\nbits’,arXiv preprint arXiv:2402.17764.\r\nWilson, J. (2026) ‘The geometry of trust: A protocol for measuring the geometric structure of\r\nAI model internals’,Tech Unfiltered Research.\r\n3\r\n",
      "status": "success",
