    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "bash",
      "code": "{\"command\": \"python -c \\\"\\nimport pypdf\\nwith open(r'C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Downloads\\\\The Binary Intent Gateway Establishing a Deterministic.pdf', 'rb') as f:\\n    reader = pypdf.PdfReader(f)\\n    print('Pages:', len(reader.pages))\\n    for i in range(min(4, len(reader.pages))):\\n        text = reader.pages[i].extract_text()\\n        if text:\\n            print('--- Page', i+1, '---')\\n            print(text[:3000])\\n\\\" 2>&1\", \"description\": \"Extract text from second Gateway PDF\"}",
      "output": "Pages: 3\r\n--- Page 1 ---\r\nThe Binary Intent Gateway: Establishing a Deterministic\r\nControl Plane for Autonomous Agents\r\nAndrea Kwabena Enning\r\nAndieKobbieTech\r\nApril 2, 2026\r\nAbstract\r\nThe rapid proliferation of autonomous agents in clinical and financial environments has\r\nexposed a fundamental architectural flaw; the reliance on In-Band Signaling for both in-\r\nstruction (Control Plane) and intent (Data Plane). This creates a structural vulnerability\r\ntermed the \"Gullibility Gap,\" which renders current LLM-based agentic systems susceptible\r\nto prompt injection and semantic drift. We introduce the Binary Intent Gateway (B.I.G.),\r\na protocol that formalises intent through a 5-bit Binary Instruction Set Architecture (ISA)\r\nand reconciles this output against an immutable Policy Manifold. By decoupling the reason-\r\ning engine from the execution gate, the B.I.G. Protocol establishes an Out-of-Band (OOB)\r\nsignaling standard. Our approach enables 99.9999% intent integrity with sub-millisecond\r\nlatency; effectively rendering current semantic-based injection vectors mathematically irrel-\r\nevant.\r\n1 Introduction\r\nThe evolution of autonomous agents mirrors the early telecommunications era; where voice data\r\nand routing instructions shared the same physical medium. This In-Band signaling enabled the\r\n\"Cap’n Crunch whistle\" exploit of the 1970s; a 2600Hz tone that hijacked the telephone switch-\r\nboard [Mui, 2025]. Modern Large Language Models (LLMs) operate on this same principle; they\r\nprocess untrusted user data and privileged system instructions as a singular, unified stream of\r\ntokens. An attacker who crafts a sufficiently persuasive input can \"whistle\" at the AI to override\r\nits internal security state.\r\nCurrent defensive strategies; such as constitutional classifiers or RLHF; function as prob-\r\nabilistic filters rather than architectural constraints. They fail to eliminate risk because they\r\noperate within the same context window as the threat. We argue that autonomous governance\r\ncannot be achieved through linguistic alignment alone; it must be enforced through structural\r\nprotocol isolation, drawing upon the deterministic control plane principles first pioneered by\r\nCisco Systems [Chakrabarty, 2026].\r\n2 The S-Hypervisor: Virtualising Security\r\nOur architecture (B.I.G.) introduces the S-Hypervisor to manage the isolation of agentic exe-\r\ncution. We treat the LLM not as a trusted entity; but as an untrusted Guest OS running in a\r\nvolatile environment.\r\n2.1 Separation of Planes\r\nThe architecture enforces a strict separation between the data and the control plane:\r\n1\r\n--- Page 2 ---\r\n•Data Plane (The Guest):Utilises a 1-bit ternary inference engine (e.g., BitNet b1.58)\r\n[Ma et al., 2024] to parse raw, untrusted human language inputs into functional intents.\r\n•Control Plane (The Gateway):An immutable, gRPC-native Policy Manifold stored\r\nin a vector-relational database. This plane is physically isolated; it holds the \"Golden\r\nIntents\" and cryptographic keys.\r\n3 Intent Normalisation (The AK-ISA)\r\nTo solve the ambiguity of natural language; the B.I.G. Protocol enforces the normalisation of\r\nintent into a discrete OpCode space. By reducing intent to a 5-bit binary representation, we\r\neliminate the linguistic entropy that allows prompt injection to succeed.\r\nOpCode Mnemonic Integrity Logic\r\n0x00 READ_UNIT Retrieval of local units\r\n0x06 WRITE_DELETE Removal (Requires Level 2 Auth)\r\n0x14 FIN_TRANS Financial Manifold Authorization\r\n0x1B GOV_RELOAD ZDPP Synchronization\r\n0x1C GOV_DEBUG Intent Ambiguity Fallback\r\nTable 1: The AK-ISA Binary Instruction Set Architecture.\r\nThe use of binary OpCodes allows for hardware-level enforcement. If an agent outputs a\r\nsequence that does not map directly to these 32 defined states; the gateway performs a hard-\r\ndrop of the packet, ensuring state integrity.\r\n4 Zero-Downtime Policy Propagation (ZDPP)\r\nTraditional infrastructure relies on batch-processed updates; which is unsuitable for real-time\r\nautonomous threats. The B.I.G. Protocol implements ZDPP to propagate security laws via\r\nhigh-speed binary streams.\r\nWhen a security policy is updated in the Git worktree; the CI/CD pipeline triggers an\r\natomic sync to all gateway nodes. Because the policy is stored as a vector-based manifold;\r\nthe propagation occurs via gRPC stream in less than 2 milliseconds; mimicking the \"vMotion\"\r\ncapabilities of enterprise virtualisation systems. This ensures the system remains protected\r\nagainst 0-day attacks without requiring a single second of downtime.\r\n5 Energy Efficiency and BitNet Integration\r\nThe B.I.G. Protocol leverages 1-bit inference kernels (BitNet b1.58) [Ma et al., 2024]. This\r\ndrastically lowers the computational energy required for intent parsing, allowing the gateway\r\nto operate on resource-constrained devices, such as mobile edge-compute nodes, at performance\r\nlevels exceeding heavy-weight models running in the cloud.\r\n6 Security Analysis: Closing the In-Band Vulnerability\r\nThe B.I.G. Protocol is inherently resistant to the \"In-Band\" injection attacks plaguing current\r\nagentic frameworks.\r\n•Memory Safety:The Gateway is implemented in Rust; which prevents buffer overflows\r\nand ensures the memory-safety of the control plane.\r\n2\r\n--- Page 3 ---\r\n•Semantic Isolation:Because the LLM (Guest) is unaware of the Routing Manifold (The\r\nLaw), an attacker cannot \"drift\" the security policy via semantic persuasion.\r\n•Deterministic Execution:By mapping human intent to a 5-bit OpCode, we achieve\r\n3rd-Normal-Form Intent (3NFI); decoupling the action from the linguistic context.\r\n7 Conclusion\r\nThe era of probabilistic AI safety is concluding. As autonomous agents scale to process millions\r\nof transactions; the requirement for deterministic governance is paramount. The B.I.G. Protocol\r\nprovides the necessary infrastructure to bridge this gap; replacing the fragile, language-based\r\nsecurity models with an immutable, binary control plane. We are not just building an interface;\r\nwe are defining the standard for the next generation of sovereign, autonomous computing.\r\nReferences\r\nChakrabarty, A. (2026). Defending 20 Trillion Transactions: How Hyperforce’s Trusted Perime-\r\nter Stops DDoS Attacks.Salesforce Engineering Blog.\r\nMa, S., Wang, H., et al. (2024). The era of 1-bit llms: All large language models are in 1.58 bits.\r\narXiv preprint arXiv:2402.17764.\r\nMui, P. (2025). Inside the brain of Agentforce: Revealing the Atlas Reasoning Engine.Salesforce\r\nEngineering Blog.\r\nWilson, J. (2026). The geometry of trust: A protocol for measuring the geometric structure of\r\nAI model internals.Tech Unfiltered.\r\n3\r\n",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1781368105351
    },
